<div id="review_3260596419" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3260596419" />
    <a title="Brittney Gibbon" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/28291083-brittney-gibbon"><img alt="Brittney Gibbon" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1582627143p2/28291083.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3260596419?book_show_action=true">Apr 03, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brittney Gibbon" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brittney Gibbon" href="/user/show/28291083-brittney-gibbon">Brittney Gibbon</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/30965675-the-blade-artist">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3260596419" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6949204343964513125"><br/>“‘You’ve nae emotional connection to anybody!’<br/>‘Anger is an emotion,’ Franco says, opening the door and exiting.”<br/><br/>And that is the Franco Begbie that I have known for the last 13 or so years; an angry, unnecessarily violent thug, with a warped moral centre and little to no regard for those around him.<br/><br/>How things change.<br/><br/>Don’t get me wrong, Bebgie is still an angry human, but these days he is channelling that rage into his art and has implemented measures to keep himself in check; staying off the pish</span>
  <span id="freeText6949204343964513125" style="display:none"><br />“‘You’ve nae emotional connection to anybody!’<br />‘Anger is an emotion,’ Franco says, opening the door and exiting.”<br /><br />And that is the Franco Begbie that I have known for the last 13 or so years; an angry, unnecessarily violent thug, with a warped moral centre and little to no regard for those around him.<br /><br />How things change.<br /><br />Don’t get me wrong, Bebgie is still an angry human, but these days he is channelling that rage into his art and has implemented measures to keep himself in check; staying off the pish, genuinely caring for his wife and daughters, a quick name change and a couple of key breathing exercises seem to be helping a lot.<br /><br />The Blade Artist offers an insight into a side of Francis Begbie that I didn’t even realise I was dying for. Flitting between his new life in California, the goings on once he heads back to Scotland, and flashbacks to his past (including memories of some favourite characters 🖤), Welsh draws a stark contrast between the two worlds and you’d almost be forgiven for blaming Edinburgh for every single poor decision Bebgie has made.<br /><br />The flashbacks to Begbie’s earlier years help to really understand where the chip on his shoulder came from, the snippets of his life in California show the man he is capable of being, and his time spent back in Scotland highlights that the man will never really change – the only difference is now his moral centre might be a little more on track.<br /><br />As usual, Welsh doesn’t shy away from the grim reality of life in this kind of circle, nor is he afraid to litter the pages with violence, drugs, drinking and his warped sense of humour. The Blade Artist is funny, it is tense, it has shocks and twists that had me had me head in hands groaning into an empty room “oh come on, now what?!” and it has moments of real, surprising emotion all driven by a theme of family and obligation.<br /><br />Welsh is my favourite author for a reason and The Blade Artist is a perfect example of why.<br /><br />“‘That’s ma name,’ Begbie admits, with a dry chortle. Jim has a nice life, he considers, but sometimes Frank has a hell of a lot more fun.”<br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /> <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6949204343964513125" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

