    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2347514955" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2347514955" />
    <a title="Kenny" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27336185-kenny"><img alt="Kenny" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2347514955?book_show_action=true">Apr 02, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kenny" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kenny" href="/user/show/27336185-kenny">Kenny</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2347514955" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10887770530543006657">Jimmy Boyle has a lot to answer for. The gang executioner (literally), introduced to art while in prison, and on release builds a career as an arty type, marrying the American art therapist - and giving rise to thousands of words about the nature of criminals, potential for reform and the importance of art and reaching out (left) and scepticism that you can&apos;t reform the fundamentally broken (right). <br/><br/>Begbie goes Boyle in the fourth Trainspotting book, and it&apos;s entirely focused on him. We meet Jim</span>
  <span id="freeText10887770530543006657" style="display:none">Jimmy Boyle has a lot to answer for. The gang executioner (literally), introduced to art while in prison, and on release builds a career as an arty type, marrying the American art therapist - and giving rise to thousands of words about the nature of criminals, potential for reform and the importance of art and reaching out (left) and scepticism that you can't reform the fundamentally broken (right). <br /><br />Begbie goes Boyle in the fourth Trainspotting book, and it's entirely focused on him. We meet Jim B(a nod to Jimmy B no doubt) in California where he's a successful artist (making sculptures of celebrities violently distorted or disfigured), then his eldest son, Sean is found dead in Edinburgh. Jim Frances gets on a plane, and over the next few days, Frank Begbie reappears.<br /><br />Without going into spoilers, there's a fair bit of writing whether Begbie has managed to tame his anger - with more development of his backstory to explain a bit more how he got that way - and hardly a shock that things do get violent (let's face it, you wouldn't read a book on Begbie without it would you? There's a few points Welsh makes around that too). There's a few places where Welsh's voice is transplanted in to Begbie's providing social commentary, but the strength in this - as with all Welsh's writing is ease with which he brings the characters and situations to life. While the ending brings together a few strands (and provides some thoughts on the debate above), it wasn't always entirely plausible - and there were a couple of pieces that were starting to hit American Psycho rather than Trainspotting, which didn't work for me. But an entertaining read. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10887770530543006657" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

