  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1647446631" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1647446631" />
    <a title="Aaron Nash" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/45707654-aaron-nash"><img alt="Aaron Nash" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1511167493p2/45707654.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1647446631?book_show_action=true">May 24, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Aaron Nash" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Aaron Nash" href="/user/show/45707654-aaron-nash">Aaron Nash</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1647446631" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12427798821175961774">I&apos;ve waited a long time for this book. Fans of Welsh, I expect, feel the same. A book based all around the life of Francis Begbie, one of Welshs most famous characters. What could possible go wrong? Well a few things actually.<br/><br/>Let&apos;s be honest we all wanted a tale of the Begbie we all know and love. The ultra violent, psycopath whom his friends and enemies both fear. The guy who if you saw in a bar you would walk out. The guy who, if you said one wrong word too, wouldn&apos;t think twice about glassing</span>
  <span id="freeText12427798821175961774" style="display:none">I've waited a long time for this book. Fans of Welsh, I expect, feel the same. A book based all around the life of Francis Begbie, one of Welshs most famous characters. What could possible go wrong? Well a few things actually.<br /><br />Let's be honest we all wanted a tale of the Begbie we all know and love. The ultra violent, psycopath whom his friends and enemies both fear. The guy who if you saw in a bar you would walk out. The guy who, if you said one wrong word too, wouldn't think twice about glassing you for being a "wide cunt." Instead we get a tale of redemption. Sort of ...<br /><br />The begbie we all know and love is gone, replaced by a family man. He now resides in L.A, a successful artist, sober and genuinely living a carefree life. After hearing about the death of his son, he has to return to Scotland, the place he left his demons and everything that shaped his previous life behind. Here he is confronted by his family, his old friends and previous employees, each of them not believing for one second this "front" that Begbie is now putting on. Is it a front though? Or has Begbie really changed? That is what the novel slowly builds towards as Begbie is constantly tested by characters from his previous life; getting wound up, being goaded into fights, signs of his old accent returning, whilst all the while we wait for the guy we all know and love to show his real face. It is a credit then that I really was not sure whether this was going to happen. Does it? Well that would be telling. <br /><br />The problem I had though was that after reading Begbie in Welshs previous novels, a tale of redemption for him is a little bit ridiculous. This character was horror personified. He had no redeeming qualities whatsoever. He loved the ultra violent lifestyle he led and that was never going to change. Also lacking from the novel was Welshs trademark humour. The previous works that begbie has appeared in I used to look forward to the chapters he appeared in, or the chapters from his point of view, because I knew that they ere going to be dark and hilarious. This is the novel that I wanted from a story that was solely from his point of view. Unfortunately it wasn't the story that we got. <br /><br />Verdict : Begbie is back! Unfortunately not as we know him. </span>
  <a data-text-id="12427798821175961774" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

